{
  "Species responding to warming are generally moving in which direction?": "",
  "Toward the equator": "",
  "Into urban areas": "",
  "Deeper underground": "",
  "Poleward and to higher elevations": "",
  "As temperatures rise, many species shift their ranges poleward and upslope to track their preferred climate conditions, a process known as tracking their climate envelope.": "",
  "Coral bleaching has led to the loss of approximately what percentage of the world's coral since 2009?": "",
  "50%": "",
  "5%": "",
  "14%": "",
  "1%": "",
  "Approximately 14% of the world's coral has been lost since 2009 due to mass bleaching events driven by marine heatwaves, representing a dramatic decline in these critical marine ecosystems.": "",
  "Climate change is expected to do what to extreme weather events?": "",
  "Increase their frequency and intensity": "",
  "Only affect tropical storms": "",
  "Decrease their frequency": "",
  "Have no measurable effect": "",
  "Climate change amplifies extreme weather by providing more energy to the atmosphere and oceans, leading to more intense heat waves, heavier rainfall events, stronger hurricanes, and more severe droughts.": "",
  "Approximately what percentage of the world's population lives in low-lying coastal areas threatened by sea level rise?": "",
  "25%": "",
  "10%": "",
  "About 10% of the global population, roughly 800 million people, lives in low-elevation coastal zones that are increasingly threatened by sea level rise, storm surge, and coastal erosion.": "",
  "The Arctic is warming at what rate compared to the global average?": "",
  "10 times faster": "",
  "2-4 times faster": "",
  "Half the rate": "",
  "The same rate": "",
  "Arctic amplification causes the Arctic to warm 2-4 times faster than the global average, primarily due to the ice-albedo feedback where melting ice exposes darker ocean surfaces that absorb more solar energy.": "",
  "Which populations are most vulnerable to heat-related mortality?": "",
  "People living in cold climates only": "",
  "Elderly, outdoor workers, and people with pre-existing health conditions": "",
  "Young athletes": "",
  "Only those in tropical regions": "",
  "The elderly, outdoor workers, urban poor, and those with pre-existing conditions are most vulnerable to heat-related illness and death because they have reduced ability to thermoregulate or limited access to cooling.": "",
  "Climate change disproportionately affects which groups?": "",
  "Developing nations and vulnerable communities": "",
  "Wealthy industrialized nations": "",
  "Only island nations": "",
  "All nations equally": "",
  "Developing nations and vulnerable communities bear the greatest climate burden despite contributing least to emissions, creating an environmental justice issue where those least responsible suffer the most.": "",
  "Warmer ocean temperatures reduce fishery productivity primarily because:": "",
  "Warmer water holds less dissolved oxygen and disrupts nutrient upwelling": "",
  "Fish prefer warm water and become too abundant": "",
  "Fishing boats cannot operate in warm water": "",
  "Warm water kills all plankton immediately": "",
  "Warmer water holds less dissolved oxygen and creates stronger stratification that inhibits nutrient upwelling from deep water, reducing primary productivity and the food base that supports commercial fish populations.": "",
  "Mountain glacier meltwater is critical for drinking water, irrigation, and hydropower on which continents?": "",
  "Only Antarctica": "",
  "Only North America": "",
  "Only Africa": "",
  "Asia, South America, and Europe": "",
  "Billions of people depend on glacial meltwater from the Himalayas, Andes, and Alps for their water supply, and accelerating glacier loss threatens long-term water security on these continents.": "",
  "Higher temperatures worsen air quality primarily through which two mechanisms?": "",
  "Increased ground-level ozone formation and more wildfire smoke": "",
  "More volcanic activity and dust storms": "",
  "More industrial emissions and vehicle exhaust": "",
  "Increased pollen and mold only": "",
  "Higher temperatures accelerate the chemical reactions that produce ground-level ozone (smog), and more frequent and intense wildfires generate PM2.5 particulate matter that degrades air quality over vast regions.": "",
  "What is phenological mismatch?": "",
  "When the timing of ecological events between interdependent species falls out of sync due to differential warming responses": "",
  "When a species migrates to the wrong location": "",
  "When two species compete for the same food source": "",
  "When predators and prey evolve different camouflage patterns": "",
  "Phenological mismatch occurs when species in an ecological relationship respond to climate change at different rates, such as when plants flower before their pollinators arrive or insect prey peaks before nesting birds need to feed their young.": "",
  "What is a climate refugee?": "",
  "An animal that migrates to escape seasonal weather": "",
  "A political leader who denies climate change": "",
  "A person displaced from their home by climate-related events such as sea level rise, drought, or extreme weather": "",
  "A scientist who studies climate change in remote areas": "",
  "Climate refugees are people forced to leave their homes due to climate-related impacts including sea level rise, desertification, extreme weather, and water scarcity, with projections suggesting hundreds of millions could be displaced by 2050.": "",
  "What is a tipping point in climate science?": "",
  "The maximum temperature a species can tolerate": "",
  "The point at which governments decide to take action": "",
  "The exact temperature at which ice begins to melt": "",
  "A threshold beyond which a climate change becomes irreversible and self-reinforcing": "",
  "A tipping point is a critical threshold in the climate system where a small additional change triggers a large, often irreversible shift, such as the collapse of an ice sheet or the dieback of the Amazon rainforest.": "",
  "What is a vector-borne disease?": "",
  "A disease spread through contaminated water": "",
  "A disease transmitted by organisms such as mosquitoes or ticks": "",
  "A disease spread through airborne particles": "",
  "A disease caused by genetic mutations": "",
  "Vector-borne diseases are illnesses transmitted to humans by organisms like mosquitoes and ticks; climate change is expanding the geographic range of these vectors, bringing diseases like malaria, dengue, and Lyme disease to new areas.": "",
  "What is food security?": "",
  "The practice of storing food in secure facilities": "",
  "The condition where all people have reliable access to sufficient, safe, and nutritious food": "",
  "The military protection of agricultural land": "",
  "The process of inspecting food for contaminants": "",
  "Food security exists when all people have physical and economic access to sufficient, safe, and nutritious food; climate change threatens food security through altered precipitation, heat stress on crops, shifting pest ranges, and extreme weather damage.": "",
  "What is environmental justice?": "",
  "The fair treatment of all people regardless of race or income in environmental policy and the distribution of environmental burdens": "",
  "Legal penalties for companies that pollute in most standard conditions": "",
  "The study of how ecosystems maintain balance as predicted by standard models": "",
  "A type of international climate agreement based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "Environmental justice is the principle that no group should bear a disproportionate share of environmental harms; climate change raises major environmental justice concerns because the poorest communities and nations suffer the most while contributing the least to emissions.": "",
  "What is a climate envelope?": "",
  "A sealed document containing climate policy goals": "",
  "The boundary layer between the atmosphere and space": "",
  "The range of temperature and precipitation conditions within which a species can survive": "",
  "A container used to ship climate research samples": "",
  "A climate envelope defines the set of climatic conditions under which a species can maintain viable populations; as climate change shifts these conditions geographically, species must migrate to follow their climate envelope or face local extinction.": "",
  "What is ocean stratification?": "",
  "The process of salt concentrating at the ocean surface": "",
  "The formation of sediment layers on the ocean floor": "",
  "The classification of ocean zones by depth": "",
  "The layering of ocean water by temperature and density that inhibits vertical mixing": "",
  "Ocean stratification is the separation of water into distinct layers based on temperature and density; warming intensifies stratification, reducing the vertical mixing that brings nutrients from deep water to the surface, thereby decreasing marine productivity.": "",
  "What is the urban heat island effect?": "",
  "A volcanic island that emits geothermal heat": "",
  "An island in the ocean that is warmer than surrounding water": "",
  "The phenomenon where urban areas are significantly warmer than surrounding rural areas due to dark surfaces and waste heat": "",
  "A tropical island experiencing above-average temperatures": "",
  "The urban heat island effect causes cities to be several degrees warmer than surrounding rural areas due to heat-absorbing dark surfaces (asphalt, rooftops), waste heat from buildings and vehicles, and reduced vegetation; climate change intensifies this effect.": "",
  "What is desertification?": "",
  "The deliberate clearing of vegetation for development": "",
  "The process by which fertile land becomes desert due to drought, deforestation, or improper agriculture, worsened by climate change": "",
  "The creation of artificial deserts for solar energy": "",
  "The natural formation of sand dunes": "",
  "Desertification is the degradation of land in arid and semi-arid regions into desert conditions; climate change accelerates this process through increased drought frequency and altered rainfall patterns, threatening food production for hundreds of millions of people.": "",
  "A farmer in sub-Saharan Africa reports that the rainy season has become shorter and more unpredictable over the past decade, causing repeated crop failures. What interconnected climate impacts is this community likely facing?": "",
  "Food insecurity, water scarcity, economic hardship, and potential displacement": "",
  "Only changes in local biodiversity": "",
  "Only reduced crop yields": "",
  "Improved conditions for drought-resistant crops": "",
  "Altered precipitation patterns trigger cascading impacts: crop failure leads to food insecurity and economic loss, reduced water availability threatens drinking supplies, and persistent conditions may force migration, demonstrating how climate change creates interconnected crises.": "",
  "A public health official in a mid-latitude city notices that dengue fever cases are appearing for the first time in the region. What climate-related mechanism most likely explains this?": "",
  "Contaminated drinking water from flooding": "",
  "Increased air pollution weakening immune systems": "",
  "International travelers bringing the disease from tropical countries": "",
  "Warmer temperatures expanding the range of Aedes mosquitoes into previously too-cool areas": "",
  "Warming temperatures allow disease-carrying mosquito species like Aedes aegypti to survive and breed in areas that were previously too cold for them, bringing tropical diseases like dengue to mid-latitude regions where populations have no prior immunity.": "",
  "A marine biologist discovers that a coral reef in the Pacific experienced bleaching during a marine heatwave, followed by ocean acidification that prevented recovery. What does this illustrate about climate change impacts?": "",
  "Ocean acidification and warming are unrelated phenomena": "",
  "Coral bleaching is always reversible": "",
  "Multiple climate stressors can interact to create compound impacts worse than either alone": "",
  "Coral reefs are not affected by climate change": "",
  "This illustrates compound impacts, where warming causes bleaching and acidification impairs the coral's ability to rebuild its skeleton, making recovery much harder; the combination of stressors is far more damaging than either would be individually.": "",
  "A wildlife manager observes that pikas (small mountain mammals) have disappeared from the lowest elevation sites in a mountain range but remain at higher elevations. What climate impact does this demonstrate?": "",
  "Predators at lower elevations are increasing": "",
  "Mining activity at lower elevations displaced them": "",
  "Warming has pushed habitat suitability upslope, creating an 'escalator to extinction' for mountaintop species": "",
  "Pikas are naturally migrating to find new food sources": "",
  "Pikas are sensitive to heat and are shifting upslope as temperatures rise, but eventually they run out of higher habitat to move to, creating what scientists call an 'escalator to extinction' for mountaintop species with nowhere left to go.": "",
  "The government of Tuvalu has begun making plans for the potential relocation of its entire population. What climate impact necessitates this extreme measure?": "",
  "Increased volcanic activity in the region": "",
  "Water pollution from industrial runoff": "",
  "Sea level rise threatening to submerge the low-lying atoll nation entirely": "",
  "Deforestation making the islands uninhabitable": "",
  "Tuvalu, with a maximum elevation of about 4.6 meters, faces existential threat from sea level rise that causes saltwater intrusion into freshwater supplies, coastal erosion, and increasingly destructive storm surges, potentially requiring the relocation of the entire nation.": "",
  "During a record-breaking heatwave in a major city, hospitals report a surge in emergency visits. The majority of patients are elderly residents from low-income neighborhoods without air conditioning. What climate and social issues does this scenario illustrate?": "",
  "A temporary weather anomaly unrelated to climate trends": "",
  "The effectiveness of urban heat island mitigation": "",
  "The intersection of climate change impacts with environmental injustice and social vulnerability": "",
  "The need for more hospitals in urban areas": "",
  "This scenario demonstrates how climate change impacts are compounded by socioeconomic inequality, as low-income communities often lack resources like air conditioning and green spaces, making them disproportionately vulnerable to heat-related health emergencies.": "",
  "A glacier in the Himalayas that feeds a major river system has lost 40% of its volume in 30 years. During the next phase, increased meltwater could cause flooding, followed by drastically reduced river flows. What communities face the greatest long-term risk?": "",
  "Coastal fishing communities downstream": "",
  "Mountain communities near the glacier summit": "",
  "Communities in the adjacent watershed": "",
  "Farming communities and cities that depend on glacial meltwater for irrigation and drinking water": "",
  "As Himalayan glaciers shrink, they initially release more meltwater (risking floods), but once the glacier is largely gone, rivers will have drastically reduced dry-season flows, threatening water security for billions of people who depend on glacial meltwater for agriculture and drinking water.": "",
  "An economist calculates that the annual cost of climate-related disasters in a country has tripled over the past 20 years. Which categories of economic loss should the analysis include?": "",
  "Only direct property damage from storms": "",
  "Infrastructure damage, agricultural losses, health costs, reduced labor productivity, and insurance losses": "",
  "Only the cost of rebuilding roads and bridges": "",
  "Only government emergency spending": "",
  "The full economic cost of climate change encompasses damage to infrastructure, crop losses, healthcare expenses, reduced worker productivity during extreme heat, rising insurance premiums, and long-term GDP reductions, projected to reach trillions of dollars globally.": "",
  "A conservation biologist notes that a frog species faces both habitat loss from deforestation and changing rainfall patterns from climate change. What concept does this illustrate?": "",
  "Multiple stressors compound biodiversity loss as climate change adds pressure to already stressed ecosystems": "",
  "Habitat loss and climate change are entirely separate issues": "",
  "Climate change is the only threat to biodiversity": "",
  "Amphibians are not affected by climate change": "",
  "Biodiversity loss is driven by multiple interacting threats including habitat destruction, pollution, overexploitation, invasive species, and climate change; when these stressors combine, their collective impact on species is far greater than any single threat alone.": "",
  "For an AP APES question, a student must explain how a 2-degree Celsius increase in global average temperature could lead to human migration. Which chain of cause and effect would earn full credit?": "",
  "Warming leads to better heating costs leads to more disposable income leads to relocation choices": "",
  "Warming leads to sea level rise and drought leads to loss of arable land and coastal flooding leads to displacement of populations": "",
  "Warming leads to longer growing seasons leads to agricultural prosperity leads to urbanization": "",
  "Warming leads to more tourism leads to economic growth leads to voluntary migration": "",
  "The AP exam rewards clear cause-and-effect reasoning: warming drives sea level rise and intensified droughts, which destroy coastal communities and arable land, forcing people to relocate as climate refugees, demonstrating systems-level thinking.": ""
